review for civilization v with gods and kingsbrave new world november 2013 civilization v may have gotten off to a rocky start the streamlined interface and the removal of staples such as unit stacking were a bit of a shock and the feeling was different with patching and updates however civilization v has grown into its own game that stands apart from its predecessors i wont say its better than previous games i wont say the historic immersion is the same although brave new world goes a long way to making that come back so unfortunately coming into civ v after playing a previous civ game will feel awkward and possibly unsatisfying but this is a game that rewards you with the time you put into it it gets better as you play it what remains missing however is the diplomacy the expansions have done a lot to repair the broken diplomacy system and it works much better than before but there remains a lack of choices for the player many systems from previous games such as spying tech stealing and religion have been restored magnificently to the game in the expansions but remain missing from the base version with brave new world a lot of the community feels that the game is now on par with the previous game civilization iv beyond the sword im not sure i agree but it certainly is a close call civilization v is far less tedious than civ iv but still not as immersive most of the complaints about civilization v come from older players familiar with older civ games but civilization v is a great starting point for the series and strategy games in general compared to similar games like europa universalis or even civilization iv civilization v is very easy to learn and has an intuitive interface and adjustable difficulty even on higher difficulty the game features unobtrusive advice which you can choose to follow no matter if youre a newcomer or a civveteran civ v still has the infamous one more turn addictiveness this series is known for and overall this is my favorite game on steam currently and i often have recommended it to people its an allaround great game  original recommendation june 2012 this is not the most satisfying civilization game it may be one of the most fun however the classic game is still there streamlined and reengineered so that less time is spent micromanaging and more time is spent planning your conquest of the world the graphics are the best of any civ game so far and there are many gameplay surprises that keep you replaying and trying out new things it is becoming one of my alltime favorites
