author background welcome to my first ever review have fun reading and hoping this review can inform andor enrich you in any way a short introduction of myself and then lets start reviewing im a 35 year old male civilizationveteran who has been playing the civfranchise since the release of the first civilization married have two adorable young sons onto hopefully my knowledge and enthousiasm might spread residing in belgium europe important changes towards previous versions the biggest and one of the best changes in my opinion are the new hexagonal tiles versus the old square tiles this concept isnt new and was already being used in other older strategyhistory gamessims it makes you wonder why it took until civ5 before using these now it feels right when moving units around the map in older versions of civ it always felt like a bit of cheating to move a unit diagonally from one square tile to another suppose you could not move diagonally you would need double the movement points to move around squares forming a corner now while you can move diagonally you gain a distinct distance advantage while doing so 14 distance against 1 while moving straight diagonalsqrt2length 1414sqrt21 in a hexagonal system movement in all 6 directions measure the same distance size does matter the most pleasant change for me was the new combat system related to distance units just how cool was it to let it rain arrows and havoc upon your foes with that newly build archery unit besieging cities is much more fun now than it used to be the fact that hills andor mountains block range doesnt only add a bit of unit realism but is definitely a very important strategic implement because of units cant form stacks on tiles anymore they should be looked at as individual armies combine this with the reduced number of tiles max 6 instead of max 8 coming from the new hex grid directly surrounding a city you really have to think twice when positioning units to launch a coordinated city assault also bearing in mind the possibility for units to retreat to safe distance for healing these changes grant so much more strategic depth than in civ5s predecessors in fact civ5 is the first version im perfectly happy with when it comes to strategy like with any other older version of the game it all looks a bit better from the maps cities units unit animations menus etc everything is visually improved content vanilla version comes with 18 civilizations with 7 civs available in dlc and respectively 9 and 9 more with the expansions gods & kings and brave new world making a total of 43 civilizations to beat the game with each of the civs having their unique leader together with hisher personal traits and unique unitsbuildings map sizes range from duel very small to huge not having checked this thoroughly my guess is that the huge map is much larger than the greatest size in civ4 and by huge i do mean huge steam hooray civilization 5 is affiliated with steam this brings the community closer to the gamer its a great resource for free downloadable mods and guides discussion forums etc basically all the advantages steam gives to a gamer can be enjoyed now as well in your favorite strategy game civ 5 should be personally i just adore the steam achievements a welcome addition in a game that can be played over and over again with randomly generated maps over time i found it rather hard to keep playing when ive beaten and lost the game so often that no realultimate goal remained steam achievements solved this motivation problem for me i also concluded my gamingstyle improved due to the variation of games i had to play to unlock achievements my ultimate goal is to unlock all 287 of them and be rewarded a perfect game hope to do this before civ 6 is released at the time im writing this review i got 96 unlocked with 203 hours played downsides yes in a game so developed and grown over even a decade there are some downsides i have to mention first of all the ai you can begin to notice repetitive predictable ai behavior having played for lets say over 150 hours this is not new in comparison to older versions and i understand this is something that can remain an issue over a longer period of time in the future from now a computer remains a programmed machine right this may not be a problem to online gamers who play against other humans but i play civ against ai for 99% of the time also when playing on higher difficulty levels the benefits the computer controlled civs get become too prominent and annoying frustrated me especially on the two highest difficulty levels immortal and deity i recommend king and emperor levels for experienced players maybe immortal on smaller andor duelsized maps deity simply is too insane to spent too much time on another minor downside may be the fact firaxis removed religion from the game in the vanilla version that is with the installment of gods & kings religion can be brought back although it is implemented differently like it was in civ4 i must add some civspecific units might be overunderpowered towards other civspecific units all in all if this is all downside i can think of firaxis created another great title conclusion a truly musthave for every fan of the civilization franchise a great recommendation for everyone who loves turnbased strategy games with the game being released for years now the civilization 5 complete pack all dlc expansions gods & kings and brave new world is regularly on sale and can be purchased for less than 15 usd 12 having bought the complete pack myself for 13 its the best 13 ever spent so far buy this asap and start growing civilized even more greetings have fun
